[[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Front Large by Radu Oltean.jpg|thumb|The Golden Helmet of Coțofenești]] The '''Golden Helmet of Coțofenești''' /kotsofeneʃti/ is a [[Getae|Geto]]-[[Dacia]]n helmet dating from the first half of the 4th century BC.
In 1929, a child named Traian Simion uncovered the helmet by chance on the territory of the village of Poiana Coțofenești (now called [[Poiana Vărbilău]]), [[Prahova County]], Romania, in the location called "Vârful Fundăturii".
Thereupon, [[Ioan Andrieșescu]], professor of Prehistory at the [[Bucharest University]] conducted a thorough investigation at the site. The team of archaeologists noticed that helmet was not part of a gold treasure or grave but it was part of a local Geto-Dacian [[La Tène]] settlement.{{sfn|Berciu|1969|p=77}} Archaeologists concluded that the helmet was a stray find, as only a few late [[Hallstatt]] pottery fragments were found, some of them wheeled. The helmet is kept at the [[National History Museum of Romania]] (inv 11420).
== Analysis == [[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Mythological Scene on the Side by Radu Oltean.jpg|thumb|left|text-top|Mythological scene on the side]] [[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti at the National Museum of Romanian History 2011 - Mythological Scene on the Back.jpg|thumb|left|text-top|Mythological scene on the back]] Almost a kilogram heavy, the gold helmet is very well preserved, missing only the part of its skull cap. The form of the helmet and its decorations reveal the autochthonous character of this Geto-Dacian artwork. The helmet is decorated with large studs on the top of the skull and two very large [[apotropaic eye]]s, meant to ward off the [[evil eye]] and magic spells.{{sfn|Berciu|1969|p=77}} It was established that it belonged to an unknown local Geto-Dacian king or to a local aristocratic noble, from around year 400 BC .{{sfn|Berciu|1969|p=77}} One theory — without any poof, however — is that this item was the sacred helmet of [[Zalmoxis]], the living god-prophet of the [[Dacians]].
[[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Front Top by Radu Oltean.jpg|thumb|text-bottom|150px|View with the damaged top.]]
Helmet decorations depict a range of mythical creatures, and an illustration, on either cheek-piece, of a ritual enactment.{{sfn|Powell|Brown|Boardman|1971|p=193}}
The cheek-pieces of the Poiana-Coțofenești helmet show a ram being sacrificed by a man who kneels on its body and is about to cut its throat with a short knife. The iconography on the right side of the helmet is of a great interest, and has been interpreted in light of the [[tauroctony]] scene from the [[Mithraic Mysteries]]. Environment and affluence might well account for a change to a larger beast in the species offered and a similar interpretation of a bull-slaying episode.{{sfn|Powell|Brown|Boardman|1971|p=193-194}} This sacrifice of the ram might have been performed by the "king-priest-god" .{{sfn|Polacco|1989|p=177}}
The pair of Voracious Beasts on the Coţofeneşti neck-guard occupy a lower register along with a similar creature deprived of a victim’s leg.{{sfn|Powell|Brown|Boardman|1971|p=193-194}} This motif of the "Voracious Beast" is found earlier in [[Assyria]]n art, and was popular among the [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscans]]. [[Phoenicia]] was probably the intermediary for its transferral to [[Italia (Roman Empire)|Italy]] and around the [[Adriatic]], but Voracious Beast must also have traveled through [[Asia Minor]] to appear in a North Thracian idiom not only on the Coţofeneşti neck-guard but also in [[high relief]] on the base of the [[Agighiol Treasure|Aghighiol beakers]] ([[Aghighiol]] is a village near the [[Danube Delta]] in eastern Romania).{{sfn|Powell|Brown|Boardman|1971|p=193-194}} [[File:Aghighiol treasure cup 2 MNIR 2012.JPG|thumb|Silver beaker from Agighiol]] [[File:Aghighiol treasure cup MNIR 2012.JPG|thumb|Silver beaker from Agighiol]] The upper register displays a row of three seated or squatting winged creatures, rather monkey-like with human faces, long forearms, and long tails. These, however, are surely direct, if run-down, descendants of the [[sphinx]]es on a [[beaker (archaeology)|gold beaker]] from [[Amlash]] .{{sfn|Powell|Brown|Boardman|1971|p=193-194}}
The eyes on a [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] battle-shield may be designated to ward off evil blows, but once translated onto a helmet, and above the eyes of a [[North Thracian]] noble who wore it, could mean "I see twice as well, I have eyes like my hawk".{{sfn|Taylor|1987|p=127}} The Thracian gold and silversmiths who manufactured the objects were aware of other contemporary art styles — those of [[Scythia]], Greece, northeast Italy and now modern Slovenia were known through trade, travel and meetings — and they adapted conventions of representation suitable for their own purposes.{{sfn|Taylor|1987|p=127}} The meaning of these motifs was no doubt context-specific.{{sfn|Taylor|1987|p=127}} [[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Archaeological sketch.jpg|thumb|Drawing of the mythological scenes in full]]
[[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Graphical Reconstruction by Radu Oltean.jpg|thumb|left|Graphic reconstruction of the damaged helmet, with the scene resembling a Mithraic tauroctony]]
The decorations such as rosette, strips, triangles, spiral and others are specific Geto-Dacian art motifs. The scene of sacrifice the ram is an oriental Iranian theme that entered in the Greek art and from there in the ‘barbarian’ art. Therefore, the helmet seems to have been realized in a Greek workshop. But, in the same time the awkward technique of execution that contrasts with the perfect technique of a Greek craftsman points out to an autochthonous one.{{sfn|Berciu|1969|p=81}}
==In popular culture== [[File:Helmet of Cotofenesti - Worn by Decebalus in the movie The Dacians.jpg|thumb|right|text-top|Incorrectly reconstructed replica, worn by [[Decebalus]] in the movie ''Dacii (The Dacians)''.]] A replica of the helmet appeared in the 1967 historical movie ''[[Dacii (film)|Dacii]]'' (''The Dacians'') by [[Sergiu Nicolaescu]], though it took place at least 500 years after the period to which the helmet has been dated. Worn by the Dacian king [[Decebalus]], the movie helmet had a flat top, an inaccuracy that entered the [[wikt:vernacular|vernacular]] of [[popular culture]]. The [[comic strip]]s "Din zori de istorie", published in late 1970s in "[[Cutezătorii]]" magazine, written by [[Vasile Mănuceanu]] and drawn by [[Albin Stănescu]], also depicts the helmet with a flat top. It is worn by the [[Getian]] king ''Odrix'' during the conflict with the [[Persia]]n king [[Darius I]] who in 513 BC was campaigning against the [[Scythians]]. The action takes place within roughly the period that produced the original helmet. A similar comic strip written by Vasile Mănuceanu and drawn by [[Sandu Florea]] depicts the king [[Burebista]] wearing the helmet as well.
